<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-289-264  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 289 264.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Lasers andamp; Optronics  May 1989 v8 n5 p22(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Tactical laser weapons: in for the soft kill? (technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Morrison, David.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The US Army's laser-based Stingray countermeasures system projecthas been cancelled for budgetary reasons.andP;  The project ran intom difficulties because Congress pressured the military toconsolidate its many overlapping programs and provide costjustifications.andP;  Stingray is designed to be mounted onlightly-armored fighting vehicles to improve their survivabilityby blinding the sensors on enemy tanks.andP;  Laser devices could alsobe adapted to blind enemy personnel.andP;  Such 'soft kill' weaponshave been given a high priority by Congress in recent years.andO;Funding for Stingray may be restored by Congressional action laterthis year.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     LasersDefense ContractsFundingWeaponsWeapons IndustryArmy.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>